div.div: Commented on #38172 Installing a tool that targets a framework not installed gives a non-actionable error message.

I have similar problem when using dotnet tool restore in a project with the following dotnet-tools.json: { "version": 1, (10 more lines were trimmed) The tool is actually installed into $HOME/.nuget/packages/cake.tools with entries for net8.0 and net9.0 . Both these SDKs are installed: .NET SDK: Version: 9.0.300 (43 more lines were trimmed) The DotnetToolSettings.xml file exists in both net8.0/any and net9.0/any folders.
Commented on #33580 Can't install tool with version containing a capital letter on Linux

@Forgind, I know it is a late comment, but what is the actual path in the file system that it throws the exception on? If the Capital part of the filename is generated in the file system with the exact content of VersionSuffix tag, then the filename would be microsoft.botsay.2.1.8-Capital.nupkg . Searching for the filename microsoft.botsay.2.1.8-capital.nupkg will then fail because Linux file system is case sensitive.
